  "prompt": "Can the statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y be justified when n>1?",
  "response": "Let's analyze this carefully:\n\n1) First, let's understand the mathematical meaning of \"n times less\"\n   \u2022 If X is n times less than Y, it would suggest X = Y/n\n\n2) Problems with this statement when n > 1:\n   \u2022 When n > 1, X would be smaller than Y\n   \u2022 However, \"n times less\" is mathematically imprecise and potentially confusing\n\n3) Mathematically correct alternatives:\n   \u2022 X is 1/n of Y\n   \u2022 X is smaller than Y by a factor of n\n   \u2022 X is n times smaller than Y is not a rigorous mathematical statement\n\n4) Example to illustrate the issue:\n   \u2022 If Y = 12 and \"X is 3 times less than Y\"\n   \u2022 This would imply X = 12/3 = 4\n   \u2022 But it's clearer and more precise to say \"X is 1/3 of Y\" or \"X is 4\"\n\n5) Conclusion:\n   \u2022 The statement \"X is n times less\" is not mathematically justifiable\n   \u2022 Use precise mathematical language instead\n\nThe statement lacks mathematical rigor and should be avoided in formal mathematical communication.",
